{{liushu|p}} – originally depicting a sacred composite creature in ancient China, combining features of the snake, crocodile, fish, deer, etc.

Shang oracle-bone and bronze forms usually show a large-mouthed beast head and an S-shaped geometric body; Shang bronzes and decorative motifs show diamond- or scale-like patterning associated with snakes (perhaps fish or crocodile scales), occasionally with legs. In oracle-bone forms, the head bears one or two inverted {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|王}}-shaped elements (i.e. inverted axe/halberd forms) or a {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|玉}}-like ornament. The form in ''Heji'' H04655 matches Shang bronze forms, which are more pictorial, like an inverted axe/halberd attached above the head; scholars generally derive this “bottle-shaped horn” from deer antlers, though some bronze forms instead attach a bell-shaped or shell-like undeciphered graph or clan emblem.

In Western Zhou bronzes, the head ornament tends toward {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|辛}}; by the late Western Zhou and early Spring and Autumn period, the mouth is drawn downward into {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|肉}}, and the body behind the head develops a large bulge, like a snake swollen after swallowing a large animal. Thereafter head and body separate into the left and right parts of the character; by the Warring States period, the S-shaped right side also acquires three horizontal strokes like a dorsal fin. In Eastern Han stelae, the right side may, perhaps for ease of writing, change into a form like {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|尨}}; Sui stelae show forms written simply as {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|尨}}. This style becomes commoner from the Song and Yuan onward; Yuan editions already show the one-stroke form {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|龙}}, later standardized in mainland China. The Japanese form {{l-lite|ja|竜}} is first attested in the 597 Sui epitaph ''Dong Meiren Muzhi'' ({{lang|zh|《董美人墓誌》}}).

===Etymology===
{{ety|zh|:inh|sit-pro:*m-bruŋ ~ m-bruk<t:dragon; thunder>}}
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*m-bru(ŋ/k)||dragon; thunder}}. Cognate with {{cog|bo|འབྲུག||dragon; thunder}}. The STEDT database also lists {{och-l|隆|gloss=thunder; sound of thunder}} and {{och-l|雹|gloss=hail}} as cognates. Also compare {{och-l|靐|gloss=sound of thunder}} and {{och-l|霹靂|gloss=thunder}}.

This word is found in many languages of the region. Compare {{cog-lite|hmx-pro|*-roŋ||dragon}} ({{cog-lite|mww|zaj}}), {{cog-lite|mkh-vie-pro|*-roːŋ||dragon}} ({{cog|vi|rồng}}), {{cog-lite|vi|thuồng luồng|'''th'''uồng '''luồng'''|serpent-like monster}}, {{cog|km|រោង||year of the dragon}}, {{cog|th|มะโรง||dragon; year of the dragon}}, {{cog|lo|ມະໂລງ||year of the dragon}}, perhaps also {{cog-lite|otk||tr=*-lan|pos=suffix denoting a wild, predatory animal}} ({{cog-lite|tr|aslan||lion}}, {{m-lite|tr|kaplan||tiger}}, {{m-lite|tr|yılan||snake}}).

